def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

  • The average number of credit cards that people have is about 5, and doesn't have any outliers of concern, with most being about 4 at 22%
  • The average visits to the bank is about 2 at 24%, and there are not outliers, so the data is also fairly normal.
  • The Total visits online is right skewed so the data will have to be normalized. We will look at removing outliers with the most frequent being 2, at 28.6%.
  • Total Calls Made is about 4 at 16.4% with not outliers.

#IQR

def treat_outliers(df, col):
    """
    treats outliers in a variable
    col: str, name of the numerical variable
    df: dataframe
    col: name of the column
    """
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1                # Inter Quantile Range (75th perentile - 25th percentile)
    lower_whisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # all the values smaller than lower_whisker will be assigned the value of lower_whisker
    # all the values greater than upper_whisker will be assigned the value of upper_whisker
    # the assignment will be done by using the clip function of NumPy
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], lower_whisker, upper_whisker)

    return df

#check the outliers

#Finding optimal no. of clusters
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(custDataScaled)
    prediction=model.predict(custDataScaled)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(custDataScaled, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / custDataScaled.shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# to visualize the elbow curve and silhouette scores
from yellowbrick.cluster import KElbowVisualizer, SilhouetteVisualizer

sil_score = []
cluster_list = list(range(2, 10))
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((custDataScaled))
    # centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_

    sil_score.append(score)

Insights - KMeans¶

  • Cluster 0:

    • This cluster contains the lowest Avg Credit limits with the Avg being about 12,000 to 15,000.
    • This cluster also contains the lowestnumber of credits cards toktal, with the average being about 2.
    • This cluster does have more visits to the Online site than cluster 1, which has more average credit limit and credit cards than cluster 0, which would indicate people that use the website more than people who do not, tend to take on less debt.
    • Total calls made is highest in this group, and it could be infered that this group is a younger group. They are making more calls, but not able to get a higher credit limit or more credit cards.

  • Cluster 1:

    • This cluster looks to have the median amount of credit limit, with the average being about 30,000.
    • They also have the median amount of total credit cards which is about 5 total.
    • This group makes the most visits to the bank, with the average being about 4, while they make the lowest online visits. It could be infered that this group might be older, and that is why they make fewer online visits and have a higher credit limit, but we would need that data to know for sure.
    • The total calls made to this group is about 2.

  • Cluster 2:

    • This cluster hase the highest average credit limit, but also many outliers. This cluster probably represents a rare type of customer that is able to take out higher credit limits for business purposes and what not.
    • Cluster 2 also has the highest number of credit cards total with the average being about 9, which would also indicate the customers represent small business owners.
    • This customer has the lowest bank visits as well as calls made, with both averages about 1, while they have the highest online visits which would indicate this group does most of their banking exclusively online.

from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import linkage, cophenet
from scipy.spatial.distance import pdist
import numpy as np

# Your data (replace this with your actual data)
#data = np.random.rand(10, 2)

# Define a list of linkage methods to test
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'ward', 'centroid']  # Add more if needed

# Calculate the pairwise distance matrix
distance_matrix = pdist(custDataScaled)

# Initialize variables to store the maximum cophenetic correlation and the best linkage method
max_coph_corr = -1
best_linkage_method = None

# Iterate over each linkage method and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for method in linkage_methods:
    Z = linkage(custDataScaled, method=method)
    c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, distance_matrix)
    
    # Check if the current linkage method gives a higher cophenetic correlation
    if c > max_coph_corr:
        max_coph_corr = c
        best_linkage_method = method

print("Best linkage method:", best_linkage_method)
print("Highest cophenetic correlation:", max_coph_corr)

Best linkage method: average
Highest cophenetic correlation: 0.9063378829906081

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]


# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage methods above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(custDataScaled, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(custDataScaled))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

Insights - Heirarchical Clustering¶

  • Cluster 0:
    • This cluster contains the lowest Avg Credit limits with the Avg being about 12,000 to 15,000.
    • This cluster also contains the lowestnumber of credits cards total, with the average being about 2.
    • This cluster has ver low banks visits with the average being 1, which and a moderate number of visits online.
    • Total calls made is highest in this group, and it could be infered that this group is a younger group. They are making more calls, but not able to get a higher credit limit or more credit cards.

  • Cluster 1:

    • This cluster hase the highest average credit limit, but also many outliers. This cluster probably represents a rare type of customer that is able to take out higher credit limits for business purposes and what not.
    • Cluster 2 also has the highest number of credit cards total with the average being about 9, which would also indicate the customers represent small business owners.
    • This customer has the lowest bank visits as well as calls made, with both averages about 1, while they have the highest online visits which would indicate this group does most of their banking exclusively online.

  • Cluster 2:

    • This cluster looks to have the median amount of credit limit, with the average being about 30,000.
    • They also have the median amount of total credit cards which is about 5 total.
    • This group makes the most visits to the bank, with the average being about 4, while they make the lowest online visits. It could be infered that this group might be older, and that is why they make fewer online visits and have a higher credit limit, but we would need that data to know for sure.
    • The total calls made to this group is about 2.

K-means vs Hierarchical Clustering¶

It apprears the the Kmeans and Heirarchical clustering result in nearly identical results, so either one could be used for observations or even using one to check and validate the results of the other.

Actionable Insights & Recommendations¶

  • There might be some value in looking more into customer demographics like age and education.
  • It seems that customers that visit the onsite bank locations have the higher avg credit limit and credit cards interms of numbers. However they do not make the most calls, so they probably are more well versed in the products.
  • The customers that make the most calls, probably with questions, visit the onlite site the most, have the least avg credit limit, total number of credit cards and do not visit the physical bank. It could be they are cimply unaware of the services that the bank provides and a simple webpage that explains the different services and products might do well for this group.
